Crimea and Sudetenland, same battle?
BRUSSELS – The annexation of Crimea by Russia constitutes the most serious example of aggression in peacetime that Europe has witnessed since the annexation of the Sudetenland by Nazi Germany in 1938.
It is certainly today customary to downplay the significance of the "lessons of Munich" when discussing this episode in which Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier yielded to Hitler's demands regarding Czechoslovakia in an attempt to appease the Führer.
However, if the Western world were to turn a blind eye to the annexation of Crimea – the second case of a Russian president, Vladimir Putin, invading sovereign territory, following the seizure of the Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008 – current democratic leaders might bitterly regret their inaction.
In Western capitals, reactions have so far been mixed.
The currently contemplated sanctions – such as expulsion from the G8, for example – might elicit laughter if the threat to peace in Europe were not so serious.
Poutine considers the collapse of the Soviet Union as the gravest catastrophe of modern times, and he strives constantly to revive a fallen Russian empire.
If the West is to be taken seriously, it will need to act with the same determination that Putin demonstrates.
The numerous successes of the Russian president within the framework of his imperialistic project have thus far cost him almost nothing.
His initiative in favor of an Eurasian Economic Community allowed Russia to rally a number of resource-rich energy states, such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
Georgia was divided in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, Russian intimidation prompted it to reject the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And here is the most precious geostrategic trophy of all – Ukraine – that could well end up in Putin's hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia "ceases to be an empire," as explained by the former US national security advisor Zbigniew Brzezinski; "on the other hand, with a corrupted and subordinated Ukraine, Russia automatically becomes an empire again." And since the vast majority of Ukrainians have no desire to join Putin's empire, it is highly likely that the country led by the Russian president is now a highly militarized state, akin to a Soviet Union without the Communist Party.
It is indispensable that the reaction of the international community live up to the degree of adventurism displayed by Putin.
cancellations of summits, proposals for trade agreements and other participations in forums as unproductive as the G8 are not sufficient.
The only procedures involving the imposition of tangible economic sanctions, which can affect Russian citizens – let us recall that they continue to re-elect Putin to power – will allow us to hope that the Kremlin will leave its expansionist trajectory.
What kind of sanctions could it be referring to?
Firstly, Turkey could decide to close the Dardanelles Strait to Russian transportation, as it did after the Russo-Georgian war in 2008.
At the time, Turkey had blocked access to the Black Sea in order to prevent the United States from intervening, even though it is now clear that this was not the intention of the United States.
Today, Turkey could choose to close the Turkish Straits not only to Russian warships but also to all commercial vessels heading to Russian ports in the Black Sea.
The impact on Russia's economy – as well as on Putin's military claims – would prove considerable.
Turkey is allowed to close the Dardanelles under an amendment added to the 1936 Montreux Convention in 1982.
Thus, Turkey could turn against Putin the very argument he invoked to justify the annexation of Crimea – namely, that it would protect the Russian ethnicities residing there – by asserting that it itself is protecting its Turkish cousins of Tatar descent, who, given the mistreatment they have suffered at the hands of Russia, clearly wish to remain under Ukrainian rule.
This week, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to turn around mid-air and headed towards Kiev to offer support to the new interim government.
The first minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, like Putin not exactly a soft touch, could thus follow suit by immediately closing the Turkish Straits to Russian transportation – until Putin recalls all his troops in Crimea to their bases, namely Sevastopol or Russia.
It would be good for Turkey to be able to rely on the guarantee conferred by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in case Russia were to try to intimidate it.
Secondly, the American president Barack Obama could impose the same type of financial sanctions on Russia that he imposed on Iran concerning its nuclear program.
These sanctions have indeed considerably invalidated the Iranian economy.
In the same way, refusing access to the American financial system to all banks conducting business with Russian banks or companies would generate an unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
The Russian citizens must understand that allowing Putin – whose rise to power was based on his promise to end the shortages of the early post-Soviet era – to pursue his aggressive imperialist course could come at a great cost to them.
Thirdly, it would be possible for Obama to remind the Chinese of their role in the stability of Eurasia.
From Putin's perspective, the disintegration of the Soviet Union constituted the most formidable geostrategic windfall that one can imagine for China.
In an instant, this empire, which had seized millions of hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries and threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation, simply vanished into thin air.
Since then, the independent Central Asian states, and Ukraine itself, have become important commercial partners of China.
The invasion of Georgia by Russia seriously upset China, as could be seen at the Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit held in the aftermath of the war (this regional bloc gathering several former Soviet states with borders adjacent to both China and Mother Russia).
Russia tried to persuade the OCS to recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
The organization, however, expressed its disagreement.
Alternatively, the Central Asian countries – Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan – would never have been able to stand up to the Kremlin without China's support.
It is now, however, up to Chinese President Xi Jinping to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's provocations.
The true test of this Chinese claim to be a genuine and responsible protagonist within the international community will indeed play out very soon at the United Nations.
Will China support this clear violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it stand in support of Ukraine's territorial integrity?
Two other avenues of sanctions are also conceivable.
Thus, each Russian leader could have their visas refused or canceled.
It would also be possible to freeze a number of assets, particularly those that have been laundered by Putin's close oligarchs.
It is only when the pain will have become unbearable, especially for the elites, that this sort of struggle that Putin is conducting today will fail.
The price of inaction could well turn out to be considerable.
The sentence translated from French to English is:  "Many countries, from Japan to Israel, rely on America's promise to act firmly against any serious threat to peace."
Moreover, when Ukraine gave up its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so on the express condition that the United States (along with the United Kingdom, France, and Russia) would guarantee its territorial integrity.
If Crimea were to remain annexed, nobody can blame Ukraine if it decides to re-nuclearize its defense (something it remains technologically capable of doing).
When Chamberlain returned from Munich, Winston Churchill addressed him with the famous formula: "You had the choice between war and dishonour."
"You chose humiliation, and you will have war." Obama and other Western leaders are now faced with a similar choice.
If they were to choose dishonor, we can be certain that the daring Putin will eventually serve them another war.
